subject: Demo showing image scaling usage for image loads
commitMessage:
Demo showing image scaling usage for image loads

This demo draws an irregular grid of images and allows the user
to cycle through all four image scaling modes per image, or for
the whole grid.

Change-Id: I50d8ef7d7a0a286e0b508cec96d5d7c769b91101
Signed-off-by: Andrew Cox <andrew.cox@partner.samsung.com>

comments.message:
Patch Set 7:

should we add all our supported formats in the demo:
jpg, png, gif, bmp, wbmp, ico... ?

Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)

> should we add all our supported formats in the demo: jpg, png, gif, bmp, wbmp, ico... ?

Well the demo is showing a feature that is orthogonal to image format so it is probably not important to have them all in other than for our own verification process: spotting regressions in the loaders.

PNG is currently avoided because it is looking wrong. An interaction between the PNG loader's cropping and the post-processing cropping to fake scaling maybe? I will fix that in an adaptor patch.

I could add at least one PNG, knowing it will look wrong for now.

The others "bmp, wbmp, ico" are avoided because there are no images of those formats in the demo repo already and I hesitate to add them (bloat). I could just convert one of the existing images to each of those formats to avoid copyright trouble if you would like one of each.

Patch Set 8:

Patch set 8 adds ico, png, bmp, and wbmp images, and restructures code and directories as indicated by previous feedback.

Patch Set 8:

See corresponding programming guide patch here:

https://review.tizen.org/gerrit/#/c/25178/

Patch Set 9: Verified+1

Demo seems to work OK, needs to be finally verified against full feature set when implemented.
Change has been successfully merged into the git repository.
